00:05:00.360 --> 00:05:02.560
after your brothers and sisters?

00:05:02.560 --> 00:05:04.360
Yes, I was the youngest.

00:05:04.360 --> 00:05:05.960
They were all working.

00:05:05.960 --> 00:05:06.800
Okay.

00:05:08.120 --> 00:05:11.600
Because there's not big age gaps between us all.

00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:14.760
There is between me and my elder brother and sister,

00:05:14.760 --> 00:05:18.120
but not as you go down the line.

00:05:18.120 --> 00:05:20.240
So they'd already got jobs by the time you left school?

00:05:20.240 --> 00:05:21.160
Yes, yeah.

00:05:21.160 --> 00:05:22.720
Were they in factories as well?

00:05:25.560 --> 00:05:28.920
My elder brother, he was a milkman at the time.

00:05:28.920 --> 00:05:33.920
He worked on the milk, and so did two of my sisters.

00:05:34.160 --> 00:05:36.560
And then Alec, the one that's just above me,

00:05:36.560 --> 00:05:38.520
he went to work on the milk for a bit,

00:05:38.520 --> 00:05:40.440
but then he went to work in the co-op,

00:05:41.640 --> 00:05:43.600
in the clothing side of it.

00:05:43.600 --> 00:05:45.800
He didn't like working on the milk.

00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:46.640
Right.

00:05:46.640 --> 00:05:50.320
And my younger brother, Stephen, he went to university.

00:05:50.320 --> 00:05:51.160
Did he?

00:05:51.160 --> 00:05:52.000
Yeah.

00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:53.440
He was a milkman.

00:05:53.440 --> 00:05:55.880
He carved out a career like that.

00:05:57.120 --> 00:05:59.560
So how did he feel like your brother going to university

00:05:59.560 --> 00:06:00.600
and you in a factory?

00:06:02.800 --> 00:06:07.800
Well, even though I started off making duffel coats,

00:06:10.840 --> 00:06:15.520
when I got to 16, the Mayfair, it was called,

00:06:15.520 --> 00:06:19.680
that closed down, and Courtauld itself took all the staff

00:06:19.680 --> 00:06:23.000
from the sewing factory on, and I went to work then

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:26.720
on two shifts, that was six or two, and two or 10.

00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:28.160
You know, like that.

00:06:28.160 --> 00:06:33.160
And I think, I don't know what, they saw something in me,

00:06:33.640 --> 00:06:37.720
and I was offered a job in the work study department.

00:06:37.720 --> 00:06:41.120
And my younger brother, Stephen,

00:06:42.560 --> 00:06:44.360
it's quite a complicated story.

00:06:44.360 --> 00:06:49.000
My mum died when he was 18 years old,

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:53.160
and he was the youngest,

00:06:53.160 --> 00:06:55.640
and he was the only one left at home then,

00:06:55.640 --> 00:06:58.720
because I'd left home and got married and that.

00:06:58.720 --> 00:07:02.400
And he used to come to my house all the time

00:07:02.400 --> 00:07:04.160
because me and him were quite close,

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:08.160
and I told him I'd been offered this job

00:07:08.160 --> 00:07:10.120
in the work study department,

00:07:10.120 --> 00:07:12.960
and I said, I can't use a slide room,

00:07:13.880 --> 00:07:18.080
because there was no computers and stuff then.

00:07:18.080 --> 00:07:20.120
You had to use a slide room.

00:07:20.120 --> 00:07:23.760
And my interview for this job was a fortnight away

00:07:23.760 --> 00:07:27.320
because Courtauld used to have a two week shutdown,

00:07:27.320 --> 00:07:30.280
and he spent the fortnight teaching me

00:07:30.280 --> 00:07:32.120
how to use the slide room.

00:07:32.120 --> 00:07:32.960
Did he?

00:07:32.960 --> 00:07:35.240
And I remember going for the interview actually,

00:07:35.240 --> 00:07:39.000
and the person that was interviewing me gave me a sum

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:42.600
that was about 10 digits long, and he was quite amazed

00:07:42.600 --> 00:07:45.120
that I just went to .8.

00:07:46.120 --> 00:07:48.360
And he looked, because I was from the factory floor,

00:07:48.360 --> 00:07:51.760
don't forget, and he looked at me quite taken aback

00:07:51.760 --> 00:07:53.000
that I got the right answer,

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:55.440
and he said, I'll just give you this other one.

00:07:55.440 --> 00:07:57.000
I said, yeah, go on then,

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:00.520
because my younger brother showed me how to use it.

00:08:00.520 --> 00:08:04.000
You know, and then I went to work in the work study.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:06.560
Wow, so you were 15 when you started in the factory then?

00:08:06.560 --> 00:08:07.400
Yes.

00:08:07.400 --> 00:08:08.360
And then when you were 16,

00:08:08.360 --> 00:08:10.840
you moved from the factory floor.

00:08:10.840 --> 00:08:15.840
I moved from an enclosed environment really

00:08:16.480 --> 00:08:20.000
in the Mayfair where we made coats.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:23.800
You just walked through Courtauld's to the top floor

00:08:23.800 --> 00:08:27.520
because it was on the top floor of a four story building.

00:08:27.520 --> 00:08:30.640
And there was machinery in that below you.

00:08:30.640 --> 00:08:35.640
You never really sort of cottoned onto that.

00:08:36.080 --> 00:08:38.040
You know, sort of cottoned onto that.

00:08:38.040 --> 00:08:40.360
You just went to the top, did you, so in.

00:08:40.360 --> 00:08:42.520
And we used to have the radio on

00:08:42.520 --> 00:08:47.520
and we'd be singing songs on the radio and things like that.

00:08:47.840 --> 00:08:50.000
And it was like a different world.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.200
And the only time you met up with anybody

00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:57.200
that was working on the factory floor was on your breaks.

00:08:57.800 --> 00:08:59.760
You know, they used to let us,

00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:01.320
because there was that many work in there.

00:09:01.320 --> 00:09:04.120
There was like 8,000 at one time

00:09:04.120 --> 00:09:06.280
working between Deeside and Aber.

00:09:07.800 --> 00:09:09.760
And they'd stagger your breaks

00:09:09.760 --> 00:09:11.600
because they couldn't have that many people

00:09:11.600 --> 00:09:15.080
turning up in the canteen or one dinner.

00:09:15.080 --> 00:09:17.800
And so you might just meet up with some

00:09:17.800 --> 00:09:18.640
that were going back,

00:09:18.640 --> 00:09:20.880
because you only had half an hour

00:09:20.880 --> 00:09:22.720
going back to their machines.

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:25.960
You know, if you knew them, all right, you know, like that.

00:09:25.960 --> 00:09:28.400
And then when you went to work with them,

00:09:28.400 --> 00:09:31.600
you were in the noise then

00:09:31.600 --> 00:09:35.240
that you'd only just sort of skirted through.

00:09:35.240 --> 00:09:39.200
And it was like a big wake-up call, I'd have to say,

00:09:39.200 --> 00:09:44.200
you know, to the conditions that they worked in downstairs.

00:09:44.320 --> 00:09:48.080
You know, they had to work faster and everything.

00:09:48.080 --> 00:09:51.120
We were like closeted really upstairs, you know,

00:09:51.120 --> 00:09:53.160
because you had targets to meet.

00:09:53.160 --> 00:09:58.160
You had to do so many cones of rayon

00:09:58.160 --> 00:10:03.160
or, you know, different, just trying to think.

00:10:04.720 --> 00:10:07.360
You'd see viscose rayon and that,

00:10:07.360 --> 00:10:09.920
and it was like a wall.

00:10:09.920 --> 00:10:11.440
And you had targets,

00:10:11.440 --> 00:10:15.480
you had to do like 30 in an hour or whatever.

00:10:15.480 --> 00:10:17.960
You had to keep the machines going.

00:10:17.960 --> 00:10:21.560
And whereas when I worked in the sewing bit,

00:10:21.560 --> 00:10:22.840
you could go for your lunch.

00:10:22.840 --> 00:10:26.200
You had to take your lunch with you most of the time

00:10:26.200 --> 00:10:28.080
because you couldn't leave their machines

00:10:28.080 --> 00:10:32.360
once you couldn't let the ends go down on them

00:10:32.360 --> 00:10:34.400
because you'd come back from that half an hour

00:10:34.400 --> 00:10:37.760
and there might be, say you were looking after 60 ends

00:10:37.760 --> 00:10:40.000
and 30 had fell down.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:41.320
What do you mean ends?

00:10:41.320 --> 00:10:45.800
Well, I showed you some pictures on my computer here.

00:10:53.080 --> 00:10:53.920
Like that.

00:10:54.840 --> 00:10:55.680
Okay.

00:10:55.680 --> 00:10:57.800
You'd be looking after the machines

00:10:57.800 --> 00:11:02.640
that was winding up the yarn onto bobbins.

00:11:02.640 --> 00:11:04.120
Right.

00:11:04.120 --> 00:11:07.960
And if they broke, you had to learn a certain knot.

00:11:07.960 --> 00:11:09.920
You couldn't just do like any old knot.

00:11:09.920 --> 00:11:12.320
They showed you this special knot

00:11:12.320 --> 00:11:15.200
and the knot had to be on the end of the cone

00:11:15.200 --> 00:11:19.800
so they could count how many knots there was on the cheese.

00:11:19.800 --> 00:11:23.120
They're called cheeses, the large ones.

00:11:23.120 --> 00:11:24.040
Right.

00:11:24.040 --> 00:11:26.440
And you could only have, say, eight knots.

00:11:26.440 --> 00:11:28.160
I can't quite remember now.

00:11:29.160 --> 00:11:30.720
Long time ago.

00:11:30.720 --> 00:11:34.120
But you couldn't really leave their machines

00:11:34.120 --> 00:11:37.080
for half an hour because you'd never catch up

00:11:37.080 --> 00:11:39.200
with your work when you got back.

00:11:39.200 --> 00:11:40.960
So were the machines still going?

00:11:40.960 --> 00:11:42.080
Yes. All the time?

00:11:42.080 --> 00:11:43.640
Yes. You didn't even switch them off

00:11:43.640 --> 00:11:44.480
to day to day? Switched them off

00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:45.560
at 10 o'clock at night.

00:11:45.560 --> 00:11:48.600
There was only two shifts where I worked,

00:11:48.600 --> 00:11:53.080
but in D-side mill, there was three shifts

00:11:53.080 --> 00:11:56.160
because the men used to come in and do the night shift.

00:11:56.160 --> 00:11:59.040
The girls would be doing the mornings

00:11:59.040 --> 00:12:02.000
and the afternoons and the men would do the nights.

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.280
And you had to leave the machine

00:12:04.280 --> 00:12:05.720
with most of the ends running

00:12:05.720 --> 00:12:08.000
because they wouldn't catch up either.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:09.480
It was like continuous.

00:12:09.480 --> 00:12:11.080
Was it? Okay.

00:12:11.080 --> 00:12:13.120
You'd have, you know, like I say,

00:12:13.120 --> 00:12:16.920
you'd maybe have to do 30 of them in an hour

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:19.040
and you'd have boxes.

00:12:19.040 --> 00:12:22.320
You'd put the cheeses in and you'd start another one.

00:12:22.320 --> 00:12:25.200
So the cheese is like the yarn, isn't it?

00:12:25.200 --> 00:12:27.720
Yes. And it had to go onto cones

00:12:28.760 --> 00:12:30.480
so that it could be taken away

00:12:30.480 --> 00:12:35.040
and then knitted into jumpers and different things, you know.

00:12:35.040 --> 00:12:37.160
Okay. So let's backtrack a minute.

00:12:38.680 --> 00:12:40.080
It's really interesting.

00:12:40.080 --> 00:12:42.360
Did you have, when you first started,

00:12:42.360 --> 00:12:44.200
did you have an interview to go there?

00:12:44.200 --> 00:12:46.240
Yes, but it was only about a 10 minute thing.

00:12:46.240 --> 00:12:48.880
Was it? Basically, you know,

00:12:49.840 --> 00:12:53.920
are you healthy? We'll just take you, measure you,

00:12:53.920 --> 00:12:57.640
take your weight, give you eyesight tests, right?

00:12:57.640 --> 00:12:58.640
You've got a job.

00:13:00.120 --> 00:13:02.680
Not like how it's done now.

00:13:02.680 --> 00:13:05.480
No. Nothing at all like it was done.

00:13:05.480 --> 00:13:08.440
So did you have any skills to give to the job?

00:13:08.440 --> 00:13:10.800
Yeah. Well, like I said,

00:13:10.800 --> 00:13:14.080
I started off in the clothing factory on the top

00:13:14.080 --> 00:13:18.080
and they paid us 50 pence on a Saturday morning

00:13:18.080 --> 00:13:20.480
because I can remember that quite well.

00:13:20.480 --> 00:13:23.320
And we used to go there and work on the machines

00:13:23.320 --> 00:13:25.280
doing these like intricate patterns.

00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:27.480
They'd give you like a piece of paper

00:13:27.480 --> 00:13:29.280
that had like a circle on it

00:13:29.280 --> 00:13:33.880
and it went into the middle or a square or something.

00:13:33.880 --> 00:13:38.480
And you had to operate the machine round this pattern

00:13:38.480 --> 00:13:40.120
and they'd come and look at it. Like a sewing machine?

00:13:40.120 --> 00:13:42.160
Yeah, sewing machine.

00:13:42.160 --> 00:13:44.720
And I mean, once you actually started on the job

00:13:44.720 --> 00:13:45.800
it was like totally different

00:13:45.800 --> 00:13:50.160
because I can remember doing a certain part of a duffel coat,

